I can't say this is a mistake, but certainly it opens a bunch of possibile continuations for black that otherwise are just impossible. The first one that comes to mind is c5. But one of the things white has to be aware is white's Bf4, which is annoying (since I normally plan to castle queenside). So...
I'll be on time to play c5 later on. And I'm giving up the queenside castling plan if this is played.
No danger on the Qside whites squares for now, and I'm ready to castle kingside, so... let's go.
Being the dsb my strongest piece, I don't want it to be exchanged or dislodged on e7 by Nb5. But if he plays it now, I plan Bb8.
You get something, you lose something. Now I'll dare him to play Nxf7.
...which he doesn't take. He is threatening again my dsb, but it can find a good square on d4, so...
Maybe Bb8 was better, with the idea of an inmediate Qc7. But it seemed to me too early.
So my c5 pawn is gone, but this gives me another useful tempo...
...and now my carabine is armed, and I can castle either sides if I need to. Castling is good... unless there is something better to play.
No kingside castling! Attack! :-) I expected Re1 at any moment, and THEN I'll castle. Queenside, of course... he doesn't seem ready for attack my Qside before I get to his Kside!
Yummy move (for me!). I didn't even think:
! He was right in not taking it, but this allows me...
No mate, but his K is wide open. Of course, Bh2+, Kh1 was just a loss of time and the chance for him to play Rg1, somehow adding defenders to his Kside, threatening g7...
Going wild... and hoping for him to exchange (he kind has to, or Qh2#).
Not Bxg4, f3, which was useless (well... if f3, Qb6+, but to open the h file for my rook seemed to me much more valuable...)

Now, unfortunately, my dsb is on the way, and I have not Bg5: he will simply play Ng3, stopping my mate threat. Now I sense it was, nevertheless, my best move. If Ne4-g3, f6 and I avoid white's following move....
This can't be bad: I threat now Ne4, and I'm bringing the other R into the action. But it allows him (my fault, how didn't I see it?)
Controlling the N's jumps, and thinking about a possible Qh4 (was it sound at some point the sac Bxf2? Probably yes!)
Threatening Nf3+, and if he exchanges BxN, my Q would be again on the dangerous diagonal.  Of course, I am saccing my lsb, but you know... there is no win with no pain :-D
...getting ready to play g5, and go on with my pressure.
Now, my Q is on another nice diagonal: if he dares to take my g5 pawn, I'll discover a check AND the h column.
...and after this, it seemed just too nice to play...
I'm sure I'll recover my piece. But I just loved those pawns... and forgot to look at the clock!
Now, it was easy to play fxN,but after Nxe4 I have no inmediate way to remove this N from the white diagonal (Rhe8 was always a threat, but it seemed to me too weak), so...
Come on! Pushing those pawns must be the way to go. I force the B's exchange....

...but now: how to retake? It took too much time, and I lost for time!!!!! Now I wonder: was I winning? How to retake the B? NxB+ was strong: If Kg1 (not wanting to get on the h column now open), Nf3+, Kg2 (now forced, or QxN and I'm up in material), Rh2#! Now I see it, it was SOOO simple!!! A pity. RxB allowed Rh1 (but Rd-h8, or even Qh6 would win), and gxB was alsowinning, threatening h3+, Kh1, and then I don't know, really, but it looks winning. I'll show the simple...
If Kh2 or Kh1 is the same story: after Nf3+, Rh2# is coming.
Only move to prolongue the agony.
...and nothing (I see) can stop Qh6 and mate. Thank you for reading.

8. Bg2 is the only move in the opening databases I use. On f3 the bishop blocks the f2 pawn and could be vulnerable to attacks by the rook down the f file. For instance 8. Bf3? 0-0 and how is white going to complete the development of the king-side?
And now he breaks with the previous game. I had to start to think. I have to deal with the threat to my d pawn.
This is the most commonly played move for white here.
Excellent move by black, it prevents his e pawn remaining backward on the semi-open file, like he mistakenly did in our last game. He played the move quickly, from memory.

And he took back instantly. Don't you just hate it when your opponent is better prepared than you? Now I had a long think. Do I take on d5 or not? If so what do I take with? Later I found this gameknot game where white took with the queen and lost quickly. http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=17990219&mv=17&rnd=0.5109989752169874 and the Gameknot computer gives 11. Qxd5 as a mistake. However there is also this game where white managed to play 11. Qxd5 and win http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=x685463&mv=21&rnd=0.5267607547382092 In the databases white normally did what I did, and play another move.
After the game Danny told me that he thought this was the best move for white. He once again played his next move very quickly, and I sunk into thought again.
What now? Eventually I moved and it was not what he had expected.....

It was this! I half expected the game to end in a quick draw now! 12....Bd7 13. Qd1 Bg4 14. Qa4+ etc. After the game Danny thought this wasn't very good, but I see now that it has been played before. White lost quickly in Bopp Thomas (2187) vs. Renner Christoph (2448) after 12.	Qa4+	b5
13.	Qxb5+	c6
14.	Qb7	O-O
15.	fxe5	Qe8
16.	Bxd5+	cxd5
17.	Qxd5+	Be6
18.	Qa5	Qc6
But Danny played this, which perhaps lets me off the hook. As well as 12.....b5!? Fritz likes 12....Nc6, another move I was thinking he may play.
He has to take this way, otherwise he just loses the knight. Now the question is - take the pawn or not take the pawn.
At the time I thought "well queens are off the board now, it is going to be hard to whip up a winning attack with the queens off" - but I was wrong! Fritz suggests 14. Be3 with slight edge to white.
Virtually forced, in order the save the bishop.
I like this move, I think it is good, and it lays a trap into which I fall. Fritz thinks Nc5 is better. Ok so where should white retreat the bishop to?
This seemed to be a mistake, but afterwards we played some variations, and white does have a tough position to play, so I am not 100% sure there is anything better. OK what did Danny play now?
Is that what you would have done?
If I had taken back with the knight he has Nf6-g4+ winning a piece.
But now he has a winning pin. Only one way to defend the bishop....
And now I can't protect it again and it is lost. I played it out, but move-by-move account is no longer necessary.

And I finally resigned. Many thanks for reading, hope you would it entertaining and educational! Please leave a comment or two and rate the annotation on the star system, to let me know how I am doing. Until next time dear reader!

Hi everyone!

Well, I am glad you have enjoyed Part 1, now here comes Part 2, I am playing against the same opponent and this game has some parallels to the last.  I thought I would play David at his own game.  The English Opening by starting with 1.c4.
4. .......Bb4 creating a potential pin on my c3 knight.

6. .... Nxb4 - after getting rid of a potential pin on my c3 knight by exchanging it for his bishop, it seems it is gonna allow one pesky knight into my position.  I kick the knight back though on the next turn.
8. e4 - finally I get this move in.
10. ...... Be6 - hitting at my c4 pawn but at least I can defend it easily with b3 or d3.  Over the next two moves I end up doing both.

12. d3 - at the moment my pawn structure seems fairly solid, but later on, just like Captain Smith of the Titanic thought, it turned out not to be the case a few moves down the line (I recently watched Cameron's 1997 movie of the Titanic recently and thought it would have some parallels here!).

13. ..... Na5 - out of nowhere David puts a lot of stress on my pawn structure.  I have a feeling that this structure is gonna be like the Titanic was just before it finally disappeared more than 12,000 feet below the sea............
15.  ....... Nxc4 - ...... breaking apart under the strain!
17. fxe3 - and now David creates more pawn islands - these are starting to look like the ice floes in the ocean that sank the Titanic!  Mayday Glenda, Mayday!
18. Qc2 -  Glenda responds to the distress rockets and desperate morse code messages sent out by these stricken footmen by desperately trying to keep them connected.
19. ...... Nc5 - uh-oh, the BQ and one remaining pesky knight is infiltrating my position, passivitis is setting in and I am really in deep water here!
20. Nd5 - but now, I try to fight back.  My knight homes in on Dave's backward c7 pawn.
22. Rb5 - setting a trap.  If 22. .....c6? then I will play Rxc5, dxc5 and then Qxa4!

23. Rxc5 - but I take anyway!  I bet you are all now thinking, what the?????  Fancy voluntarily giving up the exchange to an IM when already down on material!  But there is some method in the madness.  I do get one of my pawns back as well as the knight and the c7 pawn is very vulnerable indeed and at the moment I am tying his rook down to the defense of it.  Also, Glenda now has the opportunity to yet again make her presence felt.
25. Ne7+ - I was tempted to take off the c7 pawn at once but I had also designs on the e5 pawn and I thought I would get the knight round to the kingside to create a block as you will see.

27. Qxc7 - But the BQ has found another way to defend the e5 pawn so Glenda now takes off the c pawn.  Now I am just two points down on material and more importantly all the pawns on the queenside have been liquidated.
34. ..... Bc4+ - and now I wave the white flag as the only way to block the check is with the Q and B.  Both lead to heavy material loss.  Again, well played David.
